-- Aevum, ASX, BHP, Leighton, Stockland, Woodside: Australian Stock Preview
-- B y   S h a n i   R a j a
-- 2010-10-06T21:37:31Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-06/aevum-asx-bhp-leighton-stockland-woodside-australian-stock-preview.html
The following is a list of companies
whose shares may rise or fall in Australia. This preview
includes news announced after markets closed. All prices are
from yesterday’s close unless otherwise stated.  The S&P/ASX 200 Index  futures contract  due in December rose
0.1 percent to 4,705 as of 6:59 a.m. in Sydney. The  Bank of New
York Australia ADR Index  gained 1.6 percent. The  S&P/ASX 200
Index  climbed 1.7 percent to 4,686.80.  Mining shares: Copper rose to the highest price in almost
27 months in New York. Futures for December delivery gained 0.7
percent to close at $3.753 a pound at 1:26 p.m. on the Comex.  BHP Billiton Ltd.  (BHP AU), the world’s largest mining
company, rose 2.6 percent to A$40.53 in Sydney. Its American
depositary receipts climbed 2.4 percent in New York trading.  Rio Tinto Group  (RIO AU), the world’s third-biggest miner,
advanced 2.6 percent to A$78.99 in Sydney.  Rio is considering an emergency board meeting before a
final decision on its iron-ore joint venture with BHP, the
Australian newspaper reported, citing unnamed sources close to
both companies. The sources also said a decision would be made
only with BHP’s agreement.  Oil producers: Crude oil for November delivery rose 0.5
percent to $83.23 a barrel in New York, the highest settlement
price since May 3.  Woodside Petroleum Ltd.  (WPL AU), Australia’s second-
biggest oil and gas producer, gained 0.7 percent to A$44.80.  Gold producers: Gold rose to another record and silver
gained to a 30-year high on speculation government spending will
erode the dollar.  Newcrest Mining Ltd.  (NCM AU), Australia’s largest gold
producer, surged 3.5 percent to A$42.01.  St. Barbara Ltd.  (SBM
AU) advanced 4.9 percent to 42.5 Australian cents.  Stockland  (SGP AU):  Aevum Ltd.  (AVE AU) said its board will
unanimously recommend that all shareholders accept Stockland’s
revised offer. Shares of Stockland, Australia’s biggest
diversified property group, added 0.3 percent to A$3.93.  ASX Ltd.  (ASX AU): Australia’s main stock exchange operator
was downgraded to “underperform” from “neutral” at Credit
Suisse Group AG. Its shares climbed 2.8 percent to A$33.60.  Gunns Ltd.  (GNS AU): Australia’s largest woodchip exporter
said it’s reviewing its sawmilling, processing and retail sales
operations in Western Australia and closing the facilities is a
“real possibility.” The stock rose 1.7 percent to 60.5
Australian cents.       Leighton Holdings Ltd.  (LEI AU): Actividades de
Construccion y Servicios said its bid for Hochtief AG won’t
require an offer for the Australian subsidiary, disputing a
Hochtief claim that aims to repel the unwanted approach.
Leighton shares gained 1.8 percent to A$34.87.  To contact the reporter for this story:
